.SUBTITLE  CLEAR
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*CLEAR\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Clears the display screen of a graphics device.  If a quadrant number
is supplied, only a quarter of the screen is cleared.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 CLEAR [quadrant_number]
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8; quadrant__number
.p 0; An optional parameter that specifies which quadrant of the screen is to
be cleared. The quadrant__number should be in the range 1 to 4 where: 
.LIST " "
.LE; Quadrant__number 1 = top lefthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 2 = top righthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 3 = bottom righthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 4 = bottom lefthand quadrant
.END LIST
.LM -8
.p0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0; The CLEAR command is used to clear the display screen of a graphics device.
.P0; If an undivided screen is currently selected, the whole of the screen
is cleared.
.BR; If a divided screen is selected, then the quadrant__number parameter
specifies which quadrant is to be cleared. 
.p0; Note that it is not possible to clear a single quadrant on a TEKTRONIX
4014 display. 
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the CLEAR command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command CLEAR
No graphics device is currently enabled

*** ERROR *** Specifying command CLEAR
Command requires a quadrant number in the range 1 to 4

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*CLEAR <CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>^*ENABLE DIVIDE <CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>^*ISOMETRIC <CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*CLEAR 2<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  COLOURS
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*COLOURS\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Defines the maximum number of colours that may be used when displaying an
isometric or perspective view on a colour graphics device. 

.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 COLOURS number
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;number
.p0;The number of colours to be used for display. An integer value in the range
1 to 61 is required. 
.LM -8
.p0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0; The COLOURS command defines the maximum number of colours that will be
used when drawing a terrain view on a colour graphics device.
.p0; By default DTIVIEW uses the colour table file DTIVIEWCOL.DAT read from the
search list LSL$LOOKUP. This file contains RGB definitions for 64 display
colours. The first 3 entries define the colours 0,1 and 2 as black, white and
blue respectively; the remaining 61 entries define a series of colours that are
used when drawing the isometric or perspective view profile lines.  Different
colours are used to represent different height levels. 
.BR; Using the COLOURS command, it is possible to specify how many colours are
used when displaying a terrain view. For example, the command COLOURS 4 will
select the use of the first 4 non-special colours in the colour table (ie.
colours 3,4,5 and 6).
.BR; DTM heights of 0 and below always appear in blue. 
.P 0; The command is used either to restrict the number of colours used in the
view, or to respecify the default number of colours, when using a display device
that has fewer than 6 planes. For example on a 4 plane graphics device the
command COLOURS 13 should be used.
.P 0;Note that redefining the number of colours, may change the height
interval value previously set by the ZINTERVAL command.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the COLOURS command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command COLOURS
Command requires 1 integer argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command COLOURS
Integer value should be in the range 1 to 61

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*COLOURS 13<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.p 0
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   DESELECT FC
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESELECT FC \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Excludes an IFF feature from overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of feature code.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:         DESELECT FC feature_code [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;feature__code
.P0; An integer feature code in the range 0 to 32767. Multiple feature codes
may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of feature codes
may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. DESELECT FC 10-13 excludes feature
codes 10,11,12 and 13. 
.BR;Alternatively a valid FRT group name may be specified. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The DESELECT FC command is used to exclude IFF features from overlay on an
isometric or perspective view.  Features are excluded on the basis of their
feature code.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The DESELECT FC command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given, and the FRT command has been used to select a Feature
Representation Table.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the DESELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command is not valid unless the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been given

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command qualifiers are FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT FC 1<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT RAILWAYS<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT RIVERS 7-10,56-78\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   DESELECT FSN
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESELECT FSN \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Excludes an IFF feature from overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of feature serial number.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        DESELECT FSN fsn [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;fsn
.P0; An integer feature serial number in the range 0 to 65534. Multiple feature
serial numbers may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of
numbers may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. DESELECT FSN 10-13 excludes
feature serial numbers 10,11,12 and 13. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The DESELECT FSN command is used to exclude IFF features from overlay on an
isometric or perspective view.  Features are excluded on the basis of their
feature serial number.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The DESELECT FSN command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the DESELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command is not valid unless the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been given

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command qualifiers are FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT FSN 4\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT FSN 7-10,56-78\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   DESELECT LAYER
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESELECT LAYER \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Excludes an IFF feature from overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of layer number.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        DESELECT LAYER layer [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;layer
.p 0;An integer layer number in the range 1 to 32767. Multiple layer numbers
may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of layer numbers
may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. DESELECT LAYER 10-13 excludes all
features in layers 10,11,12 and 13. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The DESELECT LAYER command is used to exclude IFF features from overlay on
an isometric or perspective view.  Features are excluded on the basis of IFF
layer.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The DESELECT LAYER command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the DESELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command is not valid unless the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been given

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DESELECT
Command qualifiers are FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT LAYER 7\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*DESELECT LAYER 1,7-10\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   DIRECTION
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DIRECTION\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Defines the direction of view.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        DIRECTION  direction
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;direction
.p 0;A keyword defining the direction of view.  Valid keywords are
NORTH, SOUTH, EAST or WEST.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p0;The DIRECTION command defines the direction of view, and therefore
controls the order in which the DTM elevation values are sampled.
.BR;For a direction of NORTH or SOUTH, the DTM is sampled row by row; for
a direction of EAST or WEST, the DTM is sampled column by column.
.P0;The default viewing direction is from the south.
.P0;Use of the SHOW VIEW command is recommended to check on current viewing
parameters before an isometric or perspective view is generated. 
.P0;If the DTIVIEW menu has been set up on a digitising table using the SETUP
MENU command, the direction of view may be entered by means of the 4 boxes
labelled ^*N E S W\*. 
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message is specific to the DIRECTION command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command DIRECTION
Command requires a keyword qualifier of NORTH, SOUTH, EAST or WEST.

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*DIRECTION EAST\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
