.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Enables the output of a terrain view to an IFF file.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 ENABLE IFF_OUTPUT file-spec
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*
.LM +8
.P-8;file-spec
.P0; The file specification for the output IFF file.
.br; Any part of the file specification not supplied is taken from the default
'LSL$IF:IFF.IFF', although if no file-spec is supplied, you will be asked to
supply one in response to the prompt ^*Output IFF filename>\*
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P 0;ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT directs output to an IFF file when the ISOMETRIC,
PERSPECTIVE, PROFILE or OVERLAY commands are given.  This enables a terrain
view to be subsequently plotted on a device such as a drum plotter, or
manipulated using IFF utilities. 
.P 0;An IFF file holds a single terrain view, with optional overlay
information. Any overlay data is held in a separate layer to the terrain
profiles.  The commands SET LAYER, SET LAND__FC and SET SEA__FC may be
used to control into which IFF layers the data is written, and which 
feature codes are assigned to the land and sea profiles.
.P 0;The IFF file is closed using the DISABLE IFF__OUTPUT command.
.P 0;By default output to an IFF file is disabled.
.P 0;Use of the SHOW ENABLE command is recommended to check on the status of
the option before a terrain view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following message is specific to the ENABLE command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE
Command qualifiers are AUTOSCALE, BATHYMETRY, DIVIDE, FISHNET, GRAPHICS,
                       IFF_OUTPUT, OVERLAY, PRIMARY or SECONDARY

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT TEST<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  ENABLE OVERLAY
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*ENABLE OVERLAY\*
.INDEX DTIVIEW> Commands> ENABLE OVERLAY
.INDEX DTIVIEW> ENABLE CULTURE command
.LM +8
.p 0;Selects the option and activates the commands that allow vector data
to be overlaid on an isometric or perspective view.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		ENABLE OVERLAY
.end lit
.p 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p 0; The ENABLE OVERLAY command selects the option to overlay vector data
derived from an IFF file on an isometric or terrain view.  The command is
also used by the program to activate all DTIVIEW commands that are
relevant to vector overlay, such as the commands IFF, FRT and OVERLAY.
.BR; The ENABLE OVERLAY command must be given before any of the vector overlay
commands, and before generating the isometric or perspective view on which
any data is to be overlaid.
.P0; Note. The vector overlay option is supplied as a licensed facility; the
option may not be available in your version of the program. 
.P0;Use of the SHOW ENABLE command is recommended to check on the status of the
option before generating an isometric or perspective view.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the ENABLE and ENABLE OVERLAY
commands:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE
Command qualifiers are AUTOSCALE, BATHYMETRY, DIVIDE, FISHNET, GRAPHICS,
                       IFF_OUTPUT, OVERLAY, PRIMARY or SECONDARY

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE
Command qualifiers are BATHYMETRY, OVERLAY

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE OVERLAY
Vector overlay option cannot be activated

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Example:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*ENABLE OVERLAY <CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*
.bl
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   ENABLE PRIMARY
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*ENABLE PRIMARY\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Enables the use of a workstation's primary graphics device.  
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 ENABLE PRIMARY
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P 0;ENABLE PRIMARY causes output to be directed to the primary workstation
graphics device when the ISOMETRIC, PERSPECTIVE, PROFILE or OVERLAY commands
are given. 
.P 0;The command is only useful when DTIVIEW is being run on a workstation
that is configured with two graphics devices. Typically such a workstation
will consist of a monochrome and colour display; the monochrome display is
the primary device, and the colour display is the secondary device.
.p 0;On a workstation configured with a single display, the display is
the primary device. In this situation use of the commands ENABLE GRAPHICS
and DISABLE GRAPHICS to select and deselect output to the device is to
be preferred.
.P 0;By default output to the primary device is selected when the ENABLE
GRAPHICS command is given.
.P 0;Use of the SHOW ENABLE command is recommended to check on the status of
the option before a terrain view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following message is specific to the ENABLE command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE
Command qualifiers are AUTOSCALE, BATHYMETRY, DIVIDE, FISHNET, GRAPHICS,
                       IFF_OUTPUT, OVERLAY, PRIMARY or SECONDARY

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*ENABLE PRIMARY<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   ENABLE SECONDARY
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*ENABLE SECONDARY\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Enables the use of a workstation's secondary graphics device.  
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 ENABLE SECONDARY
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P 0;ENABLE SECONDARY causes output to be directed to the secondary workstation
graphics device when the ISOMETRIC, PERSPECTIVE, PROFILE or OVERLAY commands
are given. 
.P 0;The command is only useful when DTIVIEW is being run on a workstation
that is configured with two graphics devices. Typically such a workstation
will consist of a monochrome and colour display; the monochrome display is
the primary device, and the colour display is the secondary device.
.p 0;On a workstation configured with a single display, no secondary 
graphics device will exist, and the command ENABLE SECONDARY will have no
effect.
.P 0;By default output to any secondary device is selected when the ENABLE
GRAPHICS command is given.
.P 0;Use of the SHOW ENABLE command is recommended to check on the status of
the option before a terrain view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following message is specific to the ENABLE command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ENABLE
Command qualifiers are AUTOSCALE, BATHYMETRY, DIVIDE, FISHNET, GRAPHICS,
                       IFF_OUTPUT, OVERLAY, PRIMARY or SECONDARY

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*ENABLE SECONDARY<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   EXAGGERATION
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*EXAGGERATION\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Defines the vertical exaggeration that is applied to all DTM heights
when generating an isometric or perspective views.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        EXAGGERATION scale_factor
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;scale__factor
.p 0;Scale__factor defines a z scaling factor that is applied to all DTM
height values.  A real (floating point) value is required.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The EXAGGERATION command defines a z scale factor.  This is a value by
which all DTM height values are multiplied before an isometric or perspective
view is generated.
.P 0;By default no vertical exaggeration is applied ie. a z scale factor of
1 is used.
.P 0;Use of the SHOW VIEW command is recommended to check on the status of the
parameter before an isometric or perspective view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the EXAGGERATION command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command EXAGGERATION
Command requires 1 real argument

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*EXAGGERATION 2.5\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE EXIT command
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*EXIT\*
.LEFT MARGIN +8
.P0; Terminates the program.
.LEFT MARGIN -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 EXIT

.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Command parameters:\*_ None.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P0; The EXIT command is used to exit from DTIVIEW.
.br; <CTRL/Z> (pressing the Ctrl and Z keys together) may also be used to exit
from the program. 
.P 0
^^^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Messages:\*_ None.

.P0
^^^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*EXIT<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  FILEIN
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*FILEIN\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Selects and opens the input DTM that contains the terrain elevation data.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 FILEIN file-spec
.end lit
.p 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;file-spec
.P0; The file specification for the input DTM.
.br; Any part of the file specification not supplied is taken from the default
'LSL$DTI:DTI.DTI', although if no file-spec is supplied, you will be asked to
supply one in response to the prompt ^*Input DTI filename>\*
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p 0;This command opens and maps into memory a DTI file, containing the
terrain elevation data that will be used when generating an isometric or
perspective view.
.br; Details derived from the header of the file are displayed on the terminal
to confirm that the file has been successfully opened. 
.P0;If the DTM has fewer than 200 columns or 200 rows, then a default area of
interest covering the whole of the DTM is set when the file is opened. For
larger DTMs, a default area of interest defined in matrix units of bottom left
hand corner 1,1 and top right hand corner 200,200 is set after opening the
file.  This default area of interest may be redefined using the command WINDOW.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*

.P0;The following error message is specific to the FILEIN command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command FILEIN
Input DTI filename is missing

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Example:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*FILEIN TEST<CR>\*


.lit

LSL$DTI:TEST.DTI	
Header: MIKE	 Data: WORD

Units are DTI Matrix Values

Matrix Coverage    SW:    1     1    NE:   301   251
Matrix Window      SW:    1     1    NE:   200   200
Matrix Interval	    E:	  1	      N:     1
Value Range	     :      0   to    851

.end lit
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.bl
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   FRT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*FRT\*

.LM +8
.p 0; Reads a FRT (Feature Representation Table) file.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        FRT  file-spec
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;file-spec
.P0; The file specification for the FRT file. Any part of the file
specification not supplied will be taken from the default 'LSL$FRT:FRT.FRT',
although if no file-spec is supplied, you will be asked to supply one in
response to the prompt ^*Input FRT filename>\* 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;This command reads the specified Feature Representation Table.
.BR;It is only appropriate to the overlay of vector data on a terrain view.
.p 0;The entries in the FRT are used to determine the graphical representation
of IFF features.  DTIVIEW uses the table to determine the graphical type and
colour representation of any IFF features that are overlaid on the terrain
view.  The table also defines feature code group names that may be supplied as
parameters to the SELECT FC or DESELECT FC commands. 
.p 0;An FRT must be read in before the OVERLAY command is given.

.P 0;^*The command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY has been previously
given.\*
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message is specific to the FRT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command FRT
Command is not valid unless the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been given

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*FRT DTIVIEW.FRT<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  HEIGHT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*HEIGHT\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Defines the height above sea level of the view point.  The parameter
is used when generating a perspective view.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 HEIGHT height_of_view
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;height__of__view
.p 0;The height above sea level of the view point specified in metres. A real
(floating point) value is required. 
.LM -8
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0;HEIGHT defines the height of the view point.  The parameter is specified as
a height above sea level in metres. 
.P0;The parameter is used when generating a perspective view.
.P0;By default a height value of 300.0 is used.
.P 0;Use of the SHOW VIEW command is recommended to check on the status of the
parameter before an isometric or perspective view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the HEIGHT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command HEIGHT
Command requires 1 real argument

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*HEIGHT 100.5<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>

.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   HELP command
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*HELP\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Invokes help on DTIVIEW commands.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 HELP [command]

.end lit
.p 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.p -8;command
.P0; the command on which help is required
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;A brief description is given of the function and format of the specified 
command. 
.BR;If no parameter is supplied then a list of all commands available is 
given.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Messages:\*_ None. 

.P0
^^^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*HELP DISTANCE\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   IFF
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*IFF\*

.LM +8
.p 0; Opens an IFF (Internal Feature Format) file.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        IFF  file-spec
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;file-spec
.P0; The file specification  of the input IFF file. Any part of the file 
specification not supplied will be taken from the default 'LSL$IF:IFF.IFF
although if no file specification is supplied, you will be asked to supply
one in response to the prompt ^*Input IFF filename>\*
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P 0;The IFF command specifies the name of an Internal Feature Format file,
containing vector data that is to overlaid on a terrain view.
.p 0;When the command is given, a default area of interest in the IFF file
that corresponds to the IFF range entry (RA) values is set.  This may be
subsequently redefined using the IFFWINDOW command to enable the registration
of the IFF data to the DTM.
.P 0;The IFF file range and IFF window may be examined using the command
SHOW IFF.
.P 0;^*The command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been
previously given.\*
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message is specific to the IFF command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command IFF
Command is not valid unless the ENABLE OVERLAY command has been given

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*IFF SWPACE<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   IFFWINDOW
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*IFFWINDOW\*

.LM +8
.p 0; Defines an area of interest in the IFF file.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        IFFWINDOW swx swy nex ney
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;swx swy nex ney
.P0; The IFF coordinates of the south-west (bottom lefthand) and north-west
(top righthand) corners of the window. The coordinates are specified in IFF
units, as real (floating point) values.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0; IFFWINDOW is used to define a rectangular area of interest within the IFF
file. 
.BR; The window values are supplied in IFF units.
.p 0;The IFFWINDOW command enables the IFF file to be registered to the current
area of interest in the DTM. 
.BR; When the command is given, a transformation matrix for IFF to DTM
coordinate conversion is calculated, based on the 4 coordinates defining the
IFF and DTM windows. 
.P 0;The command SHOW IFF may be used to examine the IFF range and window
coordinate values.
.P 0;Before giving the command an IFF must have been selected using the IFF
command.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the IFFWINDOW command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command IFFWINDOW
Command requires 4 real arguments

*** ERROR *** Specifying command IFFWINDOW
No IFF has been specified

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*IFFWINDOW 310000.0 220000.0 270000.0 180000.0 <CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  ISOMETRIC
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*ISOMETRIC\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Generates an isometric view.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 ISOMETRIC
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0;The command ISOMETRIC is given to generate an isometric terrain view. 
.P0;The view is generated using the current viewing direction and vertical
exaggeration parameters, and using the current phi and theta rotation
values.
.P0;Only DTM nodes lying within the current DTM area of interest are
used when generating the isometric view.
.P0;The isometric view may either be output to a graphics device, or the plot
coordinates may be sent to an IFF file for subsequent plotting or
manipulation. 
.BR;Output is controlled by the ENABLE GRAPHICS and ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT
commands.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the ISOMETRIC command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ISOMETRIC
The input DTM is undefined

*** ERROR *** Specifying command ISOMETRIC
No output IFF file or graphics device has been selected.

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*ISOMETRIC<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>

.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LABEL CLEAR
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LABEL CLEAR\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Clears user annotation.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LABEL CLEAR
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.P 0;The command causes all annotation that has been generated on a graphics
screen using the LABEL command to be erased. 
.P 0;Annotation output to a Tektronix 4014 display cannot be erased 
selectively using this command.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message is specific to the LABEL command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL
Command qualifiers are CLEAR, COLOUR, POSITION, or SIZE

.END LIT
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Example:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LABEL CLEAR<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>

.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LABEL COLOUR
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LABEL COLOUR\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Selects the colour of user labelling.
.P 0;^*This command is only available on a graphics device with 8 planes\*
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LABEL COLOUR index
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;index
.P0; Index is the value of the colour index.  An integer value in the range
1 to 3 is required.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The command LABEL COLOUR determines which colour will be used to write
a label when the DRAW LABEL command is given.
.P 0;On an 8 plane graphics device, labels may be drawn in 3 different colours.
In the default colour table DTIVIEWCOL.DAT label colour 1 is defined as white;
colour 2 as red, and colour 3 as blue.  By default labels are drawn in colour
1. 
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LABEL and LABEL COLOUR
command: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL
Command qualifiers are CLEAR, COLOUR, POSITION, or SIZE

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL COLOUR
Command requires 1 integer argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL COLOUR
Command requires an integer in the range 1 to 3

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;ROVER>^*LABEL COLOUR 3<CR>\*
.br;ROVER>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LABEL POSITION
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LABEL POSITION\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Defines the position of a label on the graphics screen.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LABEL POSITION screen_x screen_y
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;screen__x, screen__y
.P0;The x y position of the label on the screen specified in normalised
device coordinates.  Both the supplied values must be in the range 0.0 to 1.0
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;LABEL POSITION defines the position of a label on the screen.  
.p0;The values are specified in normalised device coordinates. For example,
coordinates of 0.5 0.5 will write a text string with the first character
positioned in the centre of the screen. 
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LABEL and LABEL POSITION
command: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL
Command qualifiers are CLEAR, COLOUR, POSITION, or SIZE

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL POSITION
Command requires 2 real arguments

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL POSITION
Command requires 2 real arguments in the range 0 to 1

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LABEL POSITION 0.3 0.54<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LABEL SIZE
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LABEL SIZE\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Specifies the character size of text output to the screen using the DRAW
LABEL command. 
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LABEL SIZE character_size
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;character__size
.P0;The parameter character__size defines the size of the text output to the
screen.  An integer value in the range 1 to 4 is required.  Character__size 1
is the smallest and character__size 4 is the largest.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The command LABEL SIZE is used to define the size of any text output to
a graphics screen using the DRAW LABEL command.
.P 0;The character__size parameter controls the relative size of the text;
size 1 is the smallest, and size 4 is the largest.  The actual size of the
output text screen will vary with the size of the graphics device screen,
though the relative sizes of the text will remain constant.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LABEL and LABEL SIZE
commands: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL
Command qualifiers are CLEAR, COLOUR, POSITION, or SIZE

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL SIZE
Command requires 1 integer argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LABEL SIZE
Command requires an integer argument in the range 1 to 4

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LABEL SIZE 3<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LEGEND POSITION
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LEGEND POSITION\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Defines the position on the legend on the screen.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LEGEND POSITION screen_x screen_y
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;screen__x, screen__y
.P0; Screen x and y coordinates specified in normalised device units.  2 real
(floating point) values are required in the range 0.0 to 1.0
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P 0;The LEGEND POSITION command is used to control where the legend is
drawn on a graphics screen when the DRAW LEGEND command is given.
.BR; The supplied coordinates define the position of the bottom left hand
corner of the first legend box.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LEGEND and LEGEND POSITION
commands: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND
Command qualifiers are POSITION or SIZE

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND POSITION
Command requires 2 real arguments

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND POSITION
Command requires real arguments in the range 0 to 1

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LEGEND POSITION 0.2 0.5<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LEGEND SIZE
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LEGEND SIZE\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Defines the size of the legend.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		LEGEND SIZE scale_factor
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;scale__factor
.P0; A scale factor in the range 0 to 1.  A real (floating point) value is
required.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P 0;The LEGEND SIZE command is used to control the size of the legend on
the screen when the DRAW LEGEND command is given.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LEGEND and LEGEND SIZE
commands: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND
Command qualifiers are POSITION or SIZE

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND SIZE
Command requires 1 real argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LEGEND SIZE
Command requires a real argument in the range 0 to 1

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LEGEND SIZE 0.4<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   LUT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*LUT\*

.LM +8
.p 0; Selects a colour table.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        LUT  file-spec
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;file-spec
.P0; The file specification for the colour table. Any part of the file
specification not supplied will be taken from the default LSL$LOOKUP:.DAT.
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P0; This command is used to select a colour table.  The colour table is a
file containing the RGB definitions for a series of colour values.  These
colour values are used when drawing an isometric or perspective view on a
colour graphics device. 
.p 0;The default colour table which is read when a graphics device is first
enabled is DTIVIEWCOL.DAT.  Using the LUT command, an alternative colour table
may be subsequently read. 
.P 0:If a terrain view has already been output to a graphics device, the
effect of reading a new colour table using the LUT command is immediately
observed.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error message are specific to the LEGEND and LEGEND SIZE
commands: 
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command LUT
Unable to read specified colour table

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*LUT MYTABLE<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  PERSPECTIVE
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*PERSPECTIVE\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Generates a perspective view.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 PERSPECTIVE
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0;The command PERSPECTIVE is given to generate a perspective terrain view. 
.P0;The view is generated using the current viewing direction, distance,
height and vertical exaggeration parameters, and using the current phi
rotation value. These values may be examined using the SHOW VIEW command.
.P0;Only DTM nodes lying within the current DTM area of interest are
used when generating the perspective view.
.P0;The perspective view may either be output to a graphics device, or the
plot coordinates may be sent to an IFF file for subsequent plotting or
manipulation. 
.BR;Output is controlled by the ENABLE GRAPHICS and ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT
commands.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the PERSPECTIVE command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PERSPECTIVE
The input DTM is undefined

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PERSPECTIVE
No output IFF file or graphics device has been selected.

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*PERSPECTIVE<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  PHI
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*PHI\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Defines the amount of rotation applied to the terrain view in the x axis.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 PHI  rotation
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*
.LM +8
.P-8;rotation
.P0; The amount of rotation specified in degrees.  A real (floating point)
value in the range -90 to 90 degrees is required.
.LM -8
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0;The command PHI defines the degree of rotation in the x axis that is
applied to an isometric or perspective terrain view.
.P0;Applying a rotation in the x axis can be a valuable aid to interpreting a
3 dimensional view. Most frequently a rotation of 45 degrees is applied, so
that a corner of the terrain view is pointing towards the viewer. 
.P0;By default a rotation of 45 degrees is applied to all terrain views.
.BR;Use of the SHOW VIEW command is recommended to check on the x rotation
value before a terrain view is generated.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the PHI command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PHI
Command requires 1 real argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PHI
Command requires a rotation value in the range -90 to 90 degrees

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*PHI 30.0<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  PLANES
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*PHI\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Defines how many bit-planes on a graphics device are used to display a
terrain view. 
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 PLANES	 number_planes
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*
.LM +8
.P-8;number__planes
.P0;The number of bit-planes that will be used to display the terrain view. A
integer value in the range 4 to 8 is required.
.LM -8
.p0	
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P0;PLANES defines the number of bit-planes on a graphics device, and therefore
the number of colours, that will be used to display a terrain view. 
.P0;By default a set of 5 contiguous planes are allocated to the terrain view.
If 5 planes are defined, then 32 colours are available for the terrain
view, although it should be noted that only 29 colours will actually be used
when drawing the terrain surface, since the first 3 colours have a special use.
.P0; The remaining planes on a 8 bit-plane graphics device are used for the
display of any vector overlay drawn using the OVERLAY command, and for any
annotation generated using the DRAW LABEL command. With a planes setting of 5,
7 overlay and annotation colours are available.  The LABEL COLOUR command may
be used to select the annotation colour, while the colour entry in the FRT
determines in what colour, different overlay features are shown. 
.P0;It should be noted that after giving the PLANES command, a default
colour table appropriate to the number of planes, is read.  The effect of
this will either be seen immediately if a terrain view is already displayed, or
on the initialisation of the graphics device.
.B
The command PLANES 4 should be given if you are using a graphics device 
configured with 4 bit-planes.  This command will ensure that any vector
overlay
.B
Further information on the default colour tables, and the use of the PLANES
command may be found in the introductory description section. 
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the PHI command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PHI
Command requires 1 real argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PHI
Command requires a rotation value in the range -90 to 90 degrees

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*PHI 30.0<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   PROFILE
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*PROFILE\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Generates a simple profile or cross section through the DTM.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        PROFILE  x_start y_start x_end y_end
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;x__start y__start
.P0; An x y coordinate pair defining the first point of the profile.
.P-8;x__end y__end
.P0; An x y coordinate pair defining the last point of the profile.
.LM -8
.P0;The format of the command parameters is controlled by the UNITS command.
.LIST " "
.LE; UNITS MATRIX - 4 integer values are required defining the position of
the start and end points in terms of column and row numbers.
.LE; UNITS METRES - 4 real (floating point) values are required defining the
start and end points as x and y metre offsets from the SW corner of the
DTM.
.LE; UNITS SECONDS - 4 real (floating point) values are required defining the
absolute position of the start and end points in seconds of arc. The values are
supplied in the order latitude followed by longitude. A negative latitude value
indicates a position in the Southern Hemisphere, and a negative longitude value
a point to the west of Greenwich. 
.LE; UNITS LATLONG - 4 values are required defining the absolute latitude and
longitude position of the start and end points in the format DDD MM SS H where
DDD is the number of degrees, MM is the number of minutes, SS is the number of
seconds, and H is the hemisphere (N,S,E,W). The values are supplied in the
order latitude followed by longitude. 
.END LIST
.P0;Note that in all cases, the input values are adjusted to the nearest
column and row values.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P 0;The command PROFILE is given to generate a simple cross section between
two DTM node points. 
.P 0;The current vertical exaggeration value is applied to the cross section.
.P 0;The profile may be output to a graphics device, or may be sent to an IFF
file for subsequent plotting or manipulation.  
.BR;Output is controlled by the ENABLE GRAPHICS and ENABLE IFF__OUTPUT
commands. 
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the PROFILE command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PROFILE
Command requires 4 coordinate arguments

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PROFILE
Coordinate values must lie within DTM limits

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PROFILE
The input DTM is undefined

*** ERROR *** Specifying command PROFILE
No output IFF file or graphics device has been selected

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*UNITS MATRIX<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>^*PROFILE 10 10 15 33<CR>\*
.BR;DTIVIEW>

.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  QUADRANT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*QUADRANT*

.LM +8
.p 0;Selects which quadrant of a divided graphics screen will be used.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 QUADRANT quadrant_number
.end lit
.P0
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;quadrant__number
.P0;A quadrant number selecting which quadrant of the screen is to be used.
An integer value in the range 1 to 4 is required, where:
.LIST " "
.LE; Quadrant__number 1 = top lefthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 2 = top righthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 3 = bottom righthand quadrant
.LE; Quadrant__number 4 = bottom lefthand quadrant
.END LIST
.LM -8
.p0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p 0;The QUADRANT command controls which quadrant of a divided graphics screen
will be used for the display of an isometric or perspective terrain view. 
.P 0;The command is only valid if use of a quartered screen has been selected
using the ENABLE DIVIDE command.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the QUADRANT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command QUADRANT
Command requires 1 integer argument

*** ERROR *** Specifying command QUADRANT
Command requires an integer argument in the range 1 to 4

*** ERROR *** Specifying command QUADRANT
Use of a quartered screen has not been selected

.END LIT
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*QUADRANT 4<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  SELECT ALL
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SELECT ALL\*

.LM +8
.p 0; Resets all feature selections
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        SELECT ALL
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p0;SELECT ALL resets all IFF feature selections made using any of the
SELECT or DESELECT commands.
.P0;^*The SELECT ALL command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given.\*

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Message:\*_None

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT ALL <CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT FSN 7-10,56-78 <CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SHOW SELECTIONS <CR>\*
.lit
.end lit
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT ALL <CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SHOW SELECTIONS <CR>\*
.lit
.end lit
.br;DTIVIEW>

.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SELECT FC
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SELECT FC \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Includes an IFF feature for overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of feature code.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:         SELECT FC feature_code [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;feature__code
.P0; An integer feature code in the range 0 to 32767. Multiple feature codes
may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of feature codes
may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. SELECT FC 10-13 includes feature
codes 10,11,12 and 13. 
.BR;Alternatively a valid FRT group name may be specified. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The SELECT FC command is used to include an IFF feature for overlay on an
isometric or perspective view.  Features are included on the basis of their
feature code.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The SELECT FC command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given, and the FRT command has been used to specify a Feature
Representation Table.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the SELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
Command qualifiers are ALL, FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT FC 1<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT RAILWAYS<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT RIVERS 7-10,56-78\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SELECT FSN
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SELECT FSN \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Includes an IFF feature for overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of feature serial number.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        SELECT FSN fsn [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;fsn
.P0; An integer feature serial number in the range 0 to 65534. Multiple feature
serial numbers may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of
numbers may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. SELECT FSN 10-13 includes
feature serial numbers 10,11,12 and 13. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The SELECT FSN command is used to include IFF features for overlay on an
isometric or perspective view.  Features are included on the basis of their
feature serial number.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The SELECT FSN command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the SELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
Command qualifiers are ALL, FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT FSN 4\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT FSN 7-10,56-78\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SELECT LAYER
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SELECT LAYER \*

.LM +8
.p 0;Includes an IFF feature for overlay on an isometric or perspective view
on the basis of layer number.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:	        SELECT LAYER layer [,...]
.end lit
.p 0;
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\*

.LM +8
.P-8;layer
.p 0;An integer layer number in the range 1 to 32767. Multiple layer numbers
may be specified separated by commas or spaces, while a range of layer numbers
may be specified by means of a '-'. eg. SELECT LAYER 10-13 includes all
features in layers 10,11,12 and 13. 
.LM -8
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0;The SELECT LAYER command is used to include IFF features for overlay on
an isometric or perspective view.  Features are included on the basis of IFF
layer.
.P 0;By default DTIVIEW will use all features within an IFF file. 
.P 0;Use of the SHOW SELECTIONS command is recommended to display feature
selections before the OVERLAY command is given.
.P 0;The SELECT LAYER command is only valid if the ENABLE OVERLAY command has
been previously given.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the SELECT command:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
No FRT has been read

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SELECT
Command qualifiers are ALL, FC, FSN, or LAYER             

.END LIT
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.p0;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT LAYER 7\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SELECT LAYER 1,7-10\*
.br;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE  SET DEFAULT VIEW
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SET DEFAULT VIEW\*

.LM +8
.P 0;Sets all view parameters to their default values.

.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 SET DEFAULT VIEW
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Command parameters:\* _None
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p0; This command is used to set all viewing parameters to their default values.
.P0; The default viewing values may be examined using the command SHOW VIEW
after giving the SET DEFAULT VIEW command.
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\* _None
.P 0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*

.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SET DEFAULT VIEW<CR>\*
.br;DTIVIEW>^*SHOW VIEW<CR>\*
.lit
.end lit
.br;DTIVIEW>
.p 0
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SETUP MAP
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SETUP MAP\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Registers a map or other source document placed on a digitising table,
to the input DTM.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 SETUP MAP
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p 0;The SETUP MAP command allows a source document to be registered to the
input DTM.
.P0; In order to register the map and a DTM, the DTM should have first been
specified, and a source document should have been securely attached to the
surface of a digitising table. 
.P0;On giving the command you will be asked to digitise 4 rectangular
registration points. The registration points represent 
4 points on the map that correspond to the 4 corners of the DTM.  The points
are digitised in the order top left (NW), bottom left (SW), bottom right (SE)
and top right (NE) using any button on the table puck. A point should be
digitised in response to a prompt on the terminal.
.BR; An error message is generated if any of the angles of the digitised
rectangle are less than 88 degrees, or greater than 92 degrees (ie. if the
corner points of the rectangle are more than 2 degrees off rectangular). In
this case you will be asked to redigitise the 4 registration points.
.BR; Setup of the map may be aborted using <CTRL/Z> (pressing the Ctrl and Z
keys together), or by pressing ^*Button F\* on the table puck.
.p 0;Following the registration of a map to the DTM, coordinate values required
by the WINDOW command, may be input using an appropriate button on the table
puck. 

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the SETUP and SETUP MAP
commands:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SETUP
Command qualifiers are MAP or MENU

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SETUP MAP
Command is invalid if the table has not been initialised

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SETUP MAP
The input DTM must be specified before SETUP MAP

*** ERROR *** Setting up MAP
Badly digitised corner points; try again

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SETUP MAP<CR>\*
.LIT

Digitise map NW corner>

Digitise map SW corner>

Digitise map SE corner>

Digitise map NE corner>

.end lit
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SETUP MENU
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SETUP MENU\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Positions the DTIVIEW menu on the digitising table.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 SETUP MENU
.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.p 0;The SETUP MENU command allows the DTIVIEW menu to be positioned on the
digitising table.
.P0;On giving the command you will be asked to digitise the 4 corners points of
the menu. The corners are digitised in the order top left (NW), bottom left
(SW), bottom right (SE) and top right (NE) using any button on the table puck.
A point should be digitised in response to a prompt on the terminal. 
.BR; An error message is generated if any of the angles of the digitised
rectangle are less than 88 degrees, or greater than 92 degrees (ie. if the
corner points of the rectangle are more than 2 degrees off rectangular). In
this case you will be asked to redigitise the 4 menu corner points.
.BR; Setup of the menu may be aborted using <CTRL/Z> (pressing the Ctrl and Z
keys together), or by pressing ^*Button F\* on the table puck.
.P0; Once a menu has been positioned on the table, it is possible to enter
many of the DTIVIEW commands by digitising a point in the appropriate menu
box.  For commands given this way, that
require a parameter argument, you should enter the parameter using the
keyboard, in response to the prompt on the terminal.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Messages:\*
.P0;The following error messages are specific to the SETUP and SETUP MENU
commands:
.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SETUP
Command qualifiers are MAP or MENU

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SETUP MENU
Command is invalid if the table has not been initialised

*** ERROR *** Setting up MENU
Badly digitised corner points; try again

.END LIT

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SETUP MENU<CR>\*
.LIT

Digitise menu NW corner>

Digitise menu SW corner>

Digitise menu SE corner>

Digitise menu NE corner>

.end lit
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SHOW ANNOTATION command
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SHOW ANNOTATION\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Displays information on current label and legend parameters.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 SHOW ANNOTATION

.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Command parameters:\*#None.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*
.P 0;The command SHOW ANNOTATION displays information on the current position,
size and colour of a label, and the current position and size of a legend.
.BR;These parameters may be varied using the appropriate LABEL or LEGEND 
commands.
.BR;If the SHOW ANNOTATION command is given before any LABEL or LEGEND 
commands, the default annotation parameter settings may be examined.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Messages:\*

.P0;The following messages are specific to the SHOW command:

.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SHOW
Command qualifiers are ANNOTATION, ENABLE, IFF, FILEIN, SELECTIONS or VIEW

.END LIT
.P0
^^^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SHOW ANNOTATION<CR>\*

.LIT
.END LIT
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
.PAGE
.SUBTITLE   SHOW ENABLE command
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*SHOW ENABLE\*

.LM +8
.p 0;Shows the current status of those options that may be enabled by means of
the ENABLE command, or disabled using the DISABLE command.
.LM -8

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.LIT
FORMAT:		 SHOW ENABLE

.end lit
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Command parameters:\*#None.

.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*DESCRIPTION:\*

.p 0; Displays the current status of all the DTIVIEW options that may be
enabled or disabled using the ENABLE and DISABLE commands.
.BR; The name of the option is shown, followed by either the word ON or OFF
to indicate its current status.
.BR; If the command SHOW ENABLE is used before any ENABLE or DISABLE commands
have been given, the default status of the options is displayed.
.P0
^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^^^*Messages:\*

.P0;The following message is specific to the SHOW command:

.LIT

*** ERROR *** Specifying command SHOW
Command qualifiers are ANNOTATION, ENABLE, IFF, FILEIN, SELECTIONS or VIEW

.END LIT
.P0
^^^*--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\*
.BR;^*Examples:\*
             
.P0;DTIVIEW>^*SHOW ENABLE<CR>\*

.LIT

Current status:

AUTOSCALE        On        BATHYMETRY       Off      GRAPHICS         Off
IFF_OUTPUT       On        OVERLAY          Off      PRIMARY          On
SECONDARY        On

.END LIT
.BR;DTIVIEW>
.!******************************************************************************
